{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dba0e60a-59d7-4942-b33a-770c756436eb","content":"## What happened\n\n**Apple removed DSA from its native security frameworks.** On macOS, .NET's `DSA.Create()` delegates to the OS-provided crypto libraries (Apple Security/CryptoKit). Since Apple dropped DSA support, .NET throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS. Microsoft had been warning about this via obsolete attributes (`SYSLIB0030`+), and .NET 11 fully removed the fallback path.\n\nThis doesn't affect Linux (uses OpenSSL, which still supports DSA) or Windows (uses CNG, which still supports DSA).\n\n## How to fix it\n\nYou have three options, depending on your constraints:\n\n### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended for verify-only)\n\nReplace the built-in DSA with a pure managed implementation that works everywhere:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\n// Import your existing public key (from DER/PEM)\nvar pubKey = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);\nvar verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA1withDSA\"); // or SHA256withDSA\nverifier.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);\nverifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\nbool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\n### Option 2 — Use OpenSSL explicitly on macOS\n\nInstall OpenSSL via Homebrew (`brew install openssl`) and P/Invoke into it, but this adds a native dependency and deployment complexity.\n\n### Option 3 — Migrate off DSA entirely\n\nDSA is a legacy algorithm (FIPS 186-4 deprecated it in favor of ECDSA). If you control both signing and verification, re-sign with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**, which are supported on all platforms:\n\n```csharp\nusing var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create(ECCurve.NamedCurves.nistP256);\n```\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR:** Apple killed DSA → .NET 11 on macOS can't use it. Use BouncyCastle for cross-platform legacy verification, or migrate to ECDSA/Ed25519 if you can.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b11333a3-4b33-40d3-bfe3-5c6e9e4d4c0c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS when upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason about this from my knowledge.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, Microsoft began deprecating older cryptographic algorithms, and DSA specifically has been affected on macOS.\n\nThe key issue: Apple's Security framework (and CommonCrypto/CryptoKit) dropped support for DSA. On macOS, .NET relies on Apple's native crypto libraries. Since Apple removed DSA support, .NET on macOS cannot create DSA instances.\n\n\nOn macOS specifically, calling `DSA.Create()` throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` because Apple's security frameworks no longer support DSA—this was documented as a breaking change starting in .NET 7. To work around this, the user could use OpenSSL through interop, switch to a cross-platform library like BouncyCastle, or run the verification on a different platform. versions by then. Let me reconsider the timeline: .NET 7 introduced the DSA breaking change on macOS, so if it worked on .NET 10, maybe there was a compatibility layer that got removed in .NET 11. The real issue is that Apple dropped DSA from its security frameworks, which is why .NET had to stop supporting it on macOS.\n\nFor fixing this, I should outline the practical options: using BouncyCastle for a pure managed implementation, leveraging OpenSSL through P/Invoke if available, or migrating to a stronger algorithm like RSA or ECDSA. Let me give a clear, actionable answer.","outputTokens":1465,"requestId":"4016:14BAB7:1638175:1909BF8:69F94ACE"},"id":"c85cc8d4-1b03-4b51-82f6-b96abbca09be","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:42:07.825Z","parentId":"5682254d-a7e5-4a7a-872b-018d022dec9b"}
